\subsection{\href{https://beta.lmfdb.org/knowledge/show/modcurve.decomposition}{Isogeny decomposition of the Jacobian of a modular curve}}
\begin{definition}\label{modcurve.decomposition}
\uses{ag.abelian_variety,ag.dimension,ag.jacobian,av.decomposition,av.isogeny,av.simple,cmf.galois_orbit,cmf.label,cmf.newform,cmf.weight,modcurve,modcurve.genus}
As with any \hyperref[ag.abelian_variety]{abelian variety}, the \hyperref[ag.jacobian]{Jacobian} $J_H$ of a \hyperref[modcurve]{modular curve} $X_H$ can be \hyperref[av.decomposition]{decomposed} into \hyperref[av.simple]{simple} \hyperref[av.isogeny]{isogeny factors}.  For modular curves, these simple isogeny factors are modular abelian varieties corresponding to \hyperref[cmf.galois_orbit]{Galois orbits} of \hyperref[cmf.weight]{weight} 2 \hyperref[cmf.newform]{newforms}.

We list two types of information about the \textbf{isogeny decomposition} of $J_H$:

\begin{itemize}
\item  the multiset of dimensions of the simple isogeny factors: $1^3\cdot 2^2$ denotes $3$ factors of \hyperref[ag.dimension]{dimension} $1$ and $2$ factors of dimension $2$;
\item  the multiset of newforms corresponding to the modular abelian varieties in the isogeny decomposition, listed by \hyperref[cmf.label]{label}: $\texttt{11.2.a.a}^3\cdot \texttt{13.2.e.a}^2$ denotes five simple isogeny factors, three isogenous to the modular abelian variety corresponding to the newform labelled $\texttt{11.2.a.a}$ and two isogenous to the modular abelian variety corresponding to the newform labelled $\texttt{13.2.3.a}$.
\end{itemize}

When $X_H$ has \hyperref[modcurve.genus]{genus} zero, $J_H$ is the trivial abelian variety of dimension zero, and no isogeny decomposition information is listed.
\end{definition}
